  <p>The crash unfolded over three sessions. On March 25, the GSE-CI shed 875 points to 14,441, the sharpest single-day decline of 2026. On March 26, it lost another 884 points to 13,556, with GHS 44 billion in market cap erased in 48 hours. That session produced the highest single-day turnover in the exchange's history: GHS 300.5 million across 55.9 million shares. By March 27, the index had fallen further to approximately 12,990.</p>

  <p>The sell-off was led by the two heaviest-weighted stocks. Scancom PLC (MTN Ghana) fell from GHS 6.50 on March 24 to GHS 5.03 by March 27, a 22.6% decline over three sessions. GCB Bank fell GHS 4.57 in a single session on March 25, closing at GHS 41.20. The GSE Financial Stocks Index (GSE-FSI) lost 18.2% in one week, though it remained up 80.2% year to date.</p>

  <h2 id="what-drove-the-rally">What Drove the Rally</h2>

  <p>The rally from January to mid-March was extraordinary: +77% year to date. Understanding why it happened is essential to understanding why it crashed. The rally was not driven primarily by earnings growth. It was driven by three structural forces:</p>

  <p><strong>Treasury bill compression.</strong> The 91-day T-bill rate fell to 5.32% in March 2026, down from over 28% in 2024. With inflation at 3.3% (the lowest since 1999), the real return on T-bills was approximately 2%. Institutional investors holding large fixed-income portfolios were forced to find yield elsewhere. The GSE was the obvious destination.</p>

  <p><strong>Macro fundamentals.</strong> Ghana's economy posted 6.0% GDP growth in 2025 (confirmed by the Ghana Statistical Service), with non-oil GDP at 7.6%. Inflation had declined for 14 consecutive months. The Bank of Ghana cut the policy rate by a cumulative 12.5 percentage points since July 2025 (most recently to 14% in March 2026). Gross international reserves reached $14.8 billion (5.8 months of import cover). The trade surplus hit $13.66 billion for full-year 2025.</p>

  <p><strong>Post-IMF confidence.</strong> With the IMF programme exit expected in April or May 2026, a narrative of Ghana's economic recovery was firmly established. Bank lending rates fell from 30.1% to 19.2% year over year. Real private sector credit growth more than doubled.</p>

  <div class="risk-box">
    <h4>The Core Problem</h4>
    <p>Much of the rally was <strong>search-for-yield rebalancing</strong>, not a fundamental re-rating of Ghanaian companies. When institutional investors completed their portfolio shift from fixed income to equities, the buying pressure stopped. The crash was the mirror image of the rally: the same structural force, in reverse.</p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="why-it-crashed">Why It Crashed</h2>

  <p>The crash was not triggered by a single event. It was the result of four converging factors:</p>

  <p><strong>1. Search-for-yield exhaustion.</strong> The T-bill compression that drove capital into equities was a one-time portfolio rebalancing. Once institutions completed the shift, new buying pressure dried up. The marginal buyer disappeared.</p>

  <p><strong>2. Profit-taking at record levels.</strong> With the index up 77% year to date, the incentive to lock in gains was overwhelming. The March 26 session (55.9 million shares, GHS 300.5 million turnover) was the highest-volume session in GSE history, a signature of institutional, not retail, selling.</p>

  <p><strong>3. Thin market structure.</strong> The GSE remains structurally thin. MTN Ghana alone accounted for over 91% of total volume on March 27 (13.8 million shares). When a single stock dominates volume to that degree, broad-based selling can produce outsized index movements. The GSE lacks the depth and breadth to absorb large institutional outflows without violent price action.</p>

  <p><strong>4. The Hormuz overhang.</strong> The Strait of Hormuz crisis, which sent Brent crude to $112+ per barrel in the same week, introduced macroeconomic uncertainty. Fitch revised Ghana's 2026 GDP forecast down from 5.9% to 5.5%. The NPA raised diesel prices 25.7% in a single pricing window. This was not the primary cause of the sell-off, but it accelerated the timing.</p>

  <h2 id="the-cocoa-question">The Cocoa Question</h2>

  <p>There is a question GhanaWorld cannot yet fully answer: did the cocoa crisis contribute to the GSE sell-off?</p>

  <p>The timing is suspicious. Cocoa prices collapsed from over $12,000 per tonne in 2024 to approximately $2,900 by late March 2026 (before a technical rebound to $3,141). Cocobod buyer debt to banks stands at GHS 7 to 8 billion ($650 to $750 million). GCB Bank, one of the crash's leading decliners, has material exposure to cocoa sector lending.</p>

  <p>However, the sell-off was broad-based: telecoms and banking stocks fell together. There is no clean evidence that cocoa-exposed stocks fell disproportionately. This remains a Known Unknown (KU-055, KU-060 in GhanaWorld's register). We state the suspicion and the evidence gap honestly.</p>

  <h2 id="four-scenarios-from-here">Four Scenarios From Here</h2>

  <div class="data-box">
