  <p><strong>Consolidation (45%).</strong> The base case. Selling exhaustion (volume dropped 73% by March 27) suggests the institutional profit-taking wave is largely complete. If T-bill rates hold around 5% and no new shock materialises, the GSE-CI consolidates in the 12,500 to 14,000 range through Q2. The index remains up approximately 45 to 60% year to date, which is still exceptional.</p>

  <p><strong>Recovery (20%).</strong> A clean IMF exit in April or May combined with cocoa prices recovering above $3,500 per tonne could restore confidence. New earnings data from banks (particularly GCB's reported GHS 3.2 billion profit) may attract fresh buying. However, this requires the Hormuz crisis to de-escalate.</p>

  <p><strong>Deeper correction (25%).</strong> If Brent remains above $110 and the BoG pauses or reverses rate cuts at the May MPC meeting, the search-for-yield thesis breaks. Capital may flow back toward fixed income if T-bill rates rise. A cocoa price collapse below $2,500 would stress banking sector balance sheets.</p>

  <p><strong>Structural break (10%).</strong> The tail risk scenario. If Cocobod buyer debt (GHS 7 to 8 billion) triggers provisioning requirements at major banks, the banking sector, which drove the rally, becomes the source of the next leg down. This would require cocoa prices to remain depressed while Hormuz keeps fuel costs elevated: a squeeze from both sides.</p>

